brought forward the accused‚ stated the offence, and the penalty proposed—de capite, de pecunia anquirere; he then dixit diem, and on that prodixit diem, a proceeding again repeated. On the fourth occasion he gave his sentence, and if he condemned,the provocatio was fixed for the trinum nundinum (Mommsen, Staatsr. iii. 356). Thus in 56 B.c. Clodius, as curule aedile, summons Milo. The case was heard on Feb. znd and 6th‚ the final hearing fixed sor the 17th‚ and the voting for May 7th. Q. F. ii. 3. 1—-5‚ ib. 5 [7], Fam. i. 5b. 1. The curule aedile would convene the comitia tributa, the tribune the concilium plebis, unless the case was a capital one. If so, he would ask the praetor urbanus to fix a day sor the trial, which would enable him to convene the centuriata. Livy xxvi. 3, Varro, L. L. vx. 90.
